{
  "id": "study-uk-acid-001",
  "version": "1.0",
  "title": "UK Acid Rave \u2014 Hard Chemistry",
  "subtitle": "The drum machine that survived the warehouse",
  "annotation": "UK acid rave drums are not subtle. Kick hits every beat with full force \u2014 four-on-the-floor is not a choice here, it is a requirement. Snare and clap layer on 2 and 4: the snare provides the body, the clap provides the crack. Together they are louder than either alone. The hat runs 8th notes at medium velocity, with an open hat landing after beats 2 and 4 \u2014 one 16th note after the clap. This is the accent that makes rave hats sound like they're chasing the beat. The uk-acid-shuffle preset pulling those off-beats behind the grid is what makes the whole thing roll rather than rush. Remove the swing and it becomes a different record.",
  "grooveProfile": {
    "swingFeel": "Hard 38-tick shuffle on all off-beats. The most extreme swing in the collection. Off-beats sit deep behind the grid.",
    "accentLogic": "Kick and snare/clap share equal weight. The open hat accents after the clap, not before. Velocity is uniform and high.",
    "microtimingTendencies": "The shuffle is extreme enough that off-beats almost land on the triplet. The hat open arrives very late \u2014 this is intentional."
  },
